  "prompt": "How do I break down a problem and solve it with the use of Java programming?",
  "response": "To break down a problem and solve it using Java programming, you can follow a systematic approach. Here's a step-by-step guide to help you through the process:\n\n1. Understand the problem:\n   - Read and analyze the problem statement carefully.\n   - Identify the inputs and expected outputs.\n   - Note any constraints or special requirements.\n\n2. Plan the solution:\n   - Break down the problem into smaller, manageable parts.\n   - Identify the main steps or algorithms needed to solve the problem.\n   - Sketch out a high-level design or flowchart of your solution.\n\n3. Design the program structure:\n   - Determine which classes and methods you'll need.\n   - Plan the data structures to use (e.g., arrays, lists, custom objects).\n   - Consider any interfaces or abstract classes that might be useful.\n\n4. Implement the solution in Java:\n   - Start with the main class and method.\n   - Implement each part of your solution, writing clear and concise code.\n   - Use appropriate data types and Java constructs (e.g., loops, conditionals).\n\n5. Test and debug:\n   - Write test cases to verify your solution.\n   - Run the program and check the output against expected results.\n   - Debug any issues that arise, refining your code as needed.\n\n6. Optimize and refactor:\n   - Look for ways to improve the efficiency of your code.\n   - Refactor to improve readability and maintainability.\n\n7. Document your code:\n   - Add comments to explain complex parts of your code.\n   - Write a clear docstring for each method and class.\n\nLet's go through an example to illustrate this process:\n\nProblem: Write a Java program to find the factorial of a given number.\n\nStep 1: Understand the problem\n- Input: A non-negative integer\n- Output: The factorial of the input number\n- Constraint: Input must be non-negative\n\nStep 2: Plan the solution\n- The factorial of a number n is the product of all positive integers less than or equal to n.\n- We can use a loop to multiply numbers from 1 to n.\n- We need to handle the special case of 0! = 1.\n\nStep 3: Design the program structure\n- We'll create a class called FactorialCalculator.\n- It will have a static method to calculate the factorial.\n- We'll also need a main method to demonstrate the usage.\n\nStep 4: Implement the solution\n\n```java\npublic class FactorialCalculator {\n    /**\n     * Calculates the factorial of a given non-negative number.\n     * \n     * @param n The number to calculate factorial for\n     * @return The factorial of n\n     * @throws IllegalArgumentException if n is negative\n     */\n    public static long calculateFactorial(int n) {\n        if (n < 0) {\n            throw new IllegalArgumentException(\"Factorial is not defined for negative numbers\");\n        }\n        \n        if (n == 0 || n == 1) {\n            return 1;\n        }\n        \n        long result = 1;\n        for (int i = 2; i <= n; i++) {\n            result *= i;\n        }\n        \n        return result;\n    }\n\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        // Example usage\n        int number = 5;\n        long factorial = calculateFactorial(number);\n        System.out.println(\"Factorial of \" + number + \" is: \" + factorial);\n    }\n}\n```\n\nStep 5: Test and debug\n- Test the program with various inputs: 0, 1, 5, 10, 20.\n- Check for edge cases and potential overflow issues.\n\nStep 6: Optimize and refactor\n- The current implementation is straightforward and efficient for small numbers.\n- For larger numbers, we might need to use BigInteger instead of long to handle overflow.\n\nStep 7: Document the code\n- We've already added comments and a docstring for the calculateFactorial method.\n\nBy following these steps, you can systematically break down a problem and solve it using Java programming. This approach helps ensure that you create a well-structured, efficient, and maintainable solution.",
